Demo' from Aminet. After installing the demo, I found that the format
for the herb database was ok, but the ascii output was not very usable
in any other database programme for the Amiga or PC. 

So I wrote a small Arexx programme that converts the ascii output from
Twist into a human readable form.
You are free to do what you want with it, but if it is included it in
the next GHAS update, please let me know.

As I had a bit of trouble with ascii format supplied in GHAS, I loaded
the Herbs.db file into Twist, and then saved it in the 
'position dependant / horizontal' format instead of the
'quoted comma seperated' format.

Note: the input file MUST be in 'position dependant / horizontal' format.


The Arexx programme is called 'Herbex.rexx'.

The file called 'herbs.txt' MUST  be in ram: for it to work.
It saves the result called 'HERBS.ASCII' in ram:

If you like, you can change these settings, by editing the 'Herbex.rexx'
file.

The changable items are at the beginning of the programme, and are
clearly labled as follows.

                              /* CHANGABLE ITEMS */

inname  = "ram:herbs.txt"     /* input file */
outname = "ram:HERBS.ASCII"   /* output file */
pwidth  = 80                  /* desired page width BE CAREFULL */
tlines  = 994                 /* number of database records to convert */
hdext   = "_"                 /* the fill char for headings */

                              /* END CHANGABLE ITEMS */

Be a bit cautious about changing the 'pwidth' variable, as I had a bit
of trouble with the 'linewrap' section of code, and any change might
cause unpredictable results.

Anyway, I hope you find this Arexx programme of some use. I am in the
